					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">tokumaru wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Almost nothing is automatic with the NES, nearly everything must be managed by code YOU write.</div><br />[w☥]<br />The NES does a few things automatically: generating flipped versions of sprite tiles (not automatic on Sega Master System and Game Gear), compositing sprites over the background in the first place (not automatic on Apple II, ZX Spectrum, IBM PC, or anything else lacking the display list concept), loading tiles into video memory (not automatic anywhere but NES and Neo Geo), generating simple audio waveforms (not automatic on anything since the Super NES, except for handhelds), and even just rendering the next scanline (not automatic on Atari 2600).<br />[/w☥]<br /><br />tl;dr: Tokumaru is right that the NES doesn't update your display list automatically, but it could be worse.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

